The dissociation energy from the minimum of the potential well, \( D_e \), is calculated from the given dissociation energy from the ground vibrational state, \( D_0 = 2.4287  \text{eV} \), and the zero-point energy. The zero-point energy is determined using the vibrational constants \( \nu_e / c = 1405.65  \text{cm}^{-1} \) and \( \nu_e x_e / c = 23.20  \text{cm}^{-1} \).

The zero-point energy in wavenumbers is given by:
\[
E_0 = \frac{1}{2} (\nu_e / c) - \frac{1}{4} (\nu_e x_e / c) = \frac{1}{2} \times 1405.65 - \frac{1}{4} \times 23.20
\]
Calculating the terms:
\[
\frac{1}{2} \times 1405.65 = 702.825
\]
\[
\frac{1}{4} \times 23.20 = 5.800
\]
\[
E_0 = 702.825 - 5.800 = 697.025  \text{cm}^{-1}
\]

Convert \( E_0 \) from cm\(^{-1}\) to eV using the conversion factor \( 1  \text{cm}^{-1} = 1.23984193 \times 10^{-4}  \text{eV} \):
\[
E_0 = 697.025 \times 1.23984193 \times 10^{-4} = 0.086420082  \text{eV}
\]

Add \( E_0 \) to \( D_0 \):
\[
D_e = D_0 + E_0 = 2.4287 + 0.086420082 = 2.515120082  \text{eV}
\]

Considering significant figures, \( D_0 = 2.4287  \text{eV} \) has five significant figures, and the calculation yields \( D_e = 2.51512  \text{eV} \), which is rounded to five significant figures as \( 2.5151  \text{eV} \).

