Solution: The energy of one mole of photons is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{N_A h c}{\lambda}\), where \(N_A\) is Avogadro's number (\(6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}\)), \(h\) is Planck's constant (\(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s}\)), \(c\) is the speed of light (\(2.998 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}\)), and \(\lambda\) is the wavelength in meters. The wavelength is \(300 \, \text{nm} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}\).

First, compute \(h c\):  
\(h c = (6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (2.998 \times 10^8) = 1.987 \times 10^{-25} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{m}\).

Then, the energy per photon is:  
\(E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{1.987 \times 10^{-25}}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 6.623 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J}\).

For one mole of photons:  
\(E_{\text{mol}} = (6.623 \times 10^{-19}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.989 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol}\).

Convert to \(\text{kJ/mol}\):  
\(3.989 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol} = 398.9 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).

Rounding to three significant figures (based on the wavelength \(300 \, \text{nm}\) having three significant figures):  
\(398.9 \, \text{kJ/mol} \approx 399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).

Comparison: The energy of one mole of UV photons (\(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\)) is comparable to a typical single-bond energy of \(400 \, \text{kJ/mol}\), indicating that UV light at this wavelength can break such bonds.

Summary: The final answer is $399$
