The solution calculates the energy of one mole of photons with wavelength 300 nm using the formula \(E = \frac{N_A h c}{\lambda}\), resulting in \(398.9 \, \text{kJ/mol}\) after unit conversion. This value is rounded to three significant figures based on the wavelength \(300 \, \text{nm}\), giving \(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\). The comparison to the typical single-bond energy of \(400 \, \text{kJ/mol}\) is made, but the final answer for the energy calculation is \(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).

The final answer is $399$
