Problem: Calculate the magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton. Give a numerical answer.  The unit of the answer should be  $10^{-35} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~s}$.
Solution: The magnitude of the spin angular momentum for a proton is calculated using the formula \( S = \hbar \sqrt{s(s + 1)} \), where \( s = \frac{1}{2} \) is the spin quantum number. This simplifies to \( S = \hbar \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \). Using \( \hbar \approx 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \) and \( \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \approx 0.866 \), the result is approximately \( 9.133 \times 10^{-35} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \). Expressed in units of \( 10^{-35} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \) and rounded to three significant figures, the value is 9.13.

